posts.name: Kevin
posts.cooked:
We are running into a loop overrun >1 second in auto init. The only thing being called is pathplanner buildAuto, so I am wondering if anyone has experienced a similar problem before and has a suggestion for what might be particularly inefficient about what I’m doing. Is there any way to warm up auto builder beforehand? Like calling getAutonomousCommand prior to auto init?

GitHub - FIRST-Team-1699/robocats2025 here is code (dev branch)

link_counts.title: Extremely Long Auto Delay at Start
PathPlanner first path going insane - HELP!

posts.name: David Loh
posts.cooked: We had the exact same thing happen at competition. We reimaged our rio and moved getAutonomousCommand from autonomousInit to robotInit, which seemed to help, at least temporarily. See: PathPlanner first path going insane - HELP!

link_counts.title: PathPlanner first path going insane - HELP!

posts.name: Fletch
posts.cooked: You have a hard-coded auto path name, so yes you could absolutely move that buildAuto(...) call somewhere else (RobotContainer constructor for example).  Then store that command object as a member variable and return that from getAutonomousCommand().

posts.name: Kevin
posts.cooked: I’ll definitely look into doing this, and then just changing it whenever our auto chooser changes selections.

posts.name: Fletch
posts.cooked:
DL7:

moved getAutonomousCommand from autonomousInit to robotInit

I don’t recommend this.  Doing so might work in some circumstances, but if you want to use a sendable chooser or whatever, it’ll break.

posts.name: Kevin
posts.cooked: Thank you for clarifying!

posts.name: David Loh
posts.cooked: We removed our sendableChooser and hardcoded the name of our auton, but still kept the getAutonomousCommand with the hardcoded name.

posts.name: Fletch
posts.cooked: I figured given the description of what you did.  I was giving a hypothetical case where a team follows what you said then later decides they want to use a sendable choose.  I don’t recommend it because it will break in that case

posts.name: Dylan Li
posts.cooked: The quick fix for competition is to wait 5 seconds at the beginning if the overruns are dangerous to the physical robot.

posts.name: Kevin
posts.cooked: Luckily no damage, just means we only get 14 seconds to actually do auto.

posts.name: Michael Jansen
posts.cooked:
Two things that help:

Run the warmup command in robotInit

Load your autos in robot init, the run them when auto starts. Reading and parsing files is slow, so it’s best to do this ahead of time. The sendable chooser will do this.

posts.cooked: I strongly recommend AGAINST this bc the Alliance is only garunteed to be populated by the start of autonomousInit. Its very risky to do so otherwise

posts.name: David Loh
posts.cooked: We also hardcoded alliance color, and we change it before redeploying. Our loop overrun issues started at comp, and we initially thought FMS was partly to blame, so we removed all calls to the driver station that we could.

are you using ctre, and are you seeing this issue at home or at comp? there’s an issue where ctre signal logging is on by default, but only in official matches, which creates a big spike at autoinit as it tries to start writing that log file

posts.name: Kevin
posts.cooked: Just at home! We aren’t at comp yet, thankfully. We are using ctre swerve, but I didn’t see anywhere to disable logging.

posts.name: David Loh
posts.cooked: We are using CTRE , and we only see the issue at comp. How would we disable that setting?
SignalLogger.enableAutoLogging(false); at the top of robotInit()
interesting, we didn’t see it at home and nothing quite as significant that we couldn’t conceivably attribute to other factors, but it’s probably worth turning it off anyways and seeing if it helps

posts.name: David Loh
posts.cooked: Thank you! We’ll test loop times with and without it. That could explain why it was so different on FMS

posts.name: Davo
posts.cooked: The presence of the FMS don’t change the performance of any DriverStation calls. The data from the Driver Station is sent periodically to the robot, where it gets cached robot side. The robot never communicates directly with the FMS .
